problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-all-adjacent-duplicates-in-string-ii/description/
Intuition
the problem asks us to remove k consecutive indentical characters from the string , a key observation is that removing one group can make previously separated characters become adjacent , so we need a data structure that allows us to process the string while keeping track of the characters that are still alive.

this is similar to leetcode 1047 , in that problem we only needed to know whether the previous character matches the current one here we also need to know how many consecutive occurences of that character are seen .

to achieve this i use a stack where each entry stores, the character and its consecutive count

if the count becomes k i remove the entire group by popping it from the stack

otherwise if the character is different , i start a new group by pushing [character,1] onto the stack

after processing the entire string the stack contains only the characters that remain after all possible removals . finally i rebuild the answer by repeating each character according to its stored count

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n) aseach character is psuhed once and popped at most once from stack , reconstructing the final string also takes O(n) , therefore the overall time complexity is O(n)

Space complexity:
in the worst case no characters are removed so the stack stores all the charcaters requiring o(n) extra space

Code
class Solution:
    def removeDuplicates(self, s: str, k: int) -> str:
        stack = []
        for ch in s:
            if stack and stack[-1][0] == ch:
                stack[-1][1] += 1
                if stack[-1][1] == k:
                    stack.pop()
            elif not stack or stack[-1][0] != ch:
                stack.append([ch,1])
        result = ""
        for ch , count in stack:
            result += ch * count
        return result
            
